<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence submitted by Guy Newey,</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">vidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Policy Exchange </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We support the move to ensure a proper valuation of the biodiversity of development sites. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Linked to this is the importance of ensuring that valuations are conducted by appropriately experienced, qualified and independent professionals.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A registry of biodiversity offset schemes is essential to ensure transparency and avoid the same offset being offered to multiple developers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We consider that the current Green Paper’s proposals for net gain of biodiversity in offsets could be further strengthened.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We support the introduction of a mandatory system of offsetting, as this would help stimulate innovation and prevent a bottleneck in offset providers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policy Exchange is the UK’s leading think tank. As an educational charity our mission is to develop and promote new policy ideas which deliver better public services, a stronger society and a more dynamic economy. Our research is independent and evidence-based and we share our ideas with policy makers from all sides of the political spectrum. Our research is strictly empirical and we do not take commissions. This allows us to be completely independent and make workable policy recommendations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policy Exchange’s Environment &amp; Energy Unit conducts innovative and independent policy research into a wide range of environmental, infrastructure and regulatory challenges. Our objective is to influence policy making and to shape debate. A key focus of our work is to identify ways to tackle environmental challenges effectively, while minimising adverse impact on living standards. We promote well-designed regulation to exploit the power of markets to achieve environmental outcomes innovatively and cost-effectively. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Within this context, we see biodiversity offsetting as a potentially important mechanism for delivering both gains for the economy and biodiversity within the planning system. We have considered biodiversity offsets within our report on biodiversity in the planning system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Nurturing Nature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">available to download from our website: </span><a href="http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/publications/category/item/nurturing-nature?category_id=24"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/publications/category/item/nurturing-nature?category_id=24</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of Interests</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have no interests to declare with regard to biodiversity offsetting.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Natural Capital</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We consider that the continued undervaluation of biodiversity in conventional economic analysis will result in continued biodiversity loss, due to an inability to compete with other priorities (such as transport and housing) for limited funding resources.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a result, we welcome the Government’s efforts to introduce biodiversity offsetting: a means by which the value of biodiversity (in this case, primarily habitats) is measured and residual biodiversity loss as a result of development compensated for off-site (although only after the mitigation hierarchy has first been applied).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A well-designed and implemented biodiversity offset system should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure that development, at the margin, is pushed towards low quality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(in terms of biodiversity) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">land, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whether</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">brownfield</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greenfield</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> land</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, to ensure that a site’s biodiversity value has been correctly valued, it is imperative that the initial valuations be made by suitably experienced, qualified and independent professionals. Without this requirement, a biodiversity offset system will not be consistent, reputable and trusted by the public or green NGOs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biodiversity Offset </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Registry</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our work investigating biodiversity in the planning system revealed that the key weaknesses of the current planning system for biodiversity protection and enhancement are the lack of transparency, poor monitoring and little or no enforcement of compensation agreements. A Freedom of Information request to 354 local planning authorities (with a 94% response rate) found evidence of only one enforcement measure and 74% of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the identified compensation measures did not provide any evidence of monitoring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is compounded by the lack of records and evaluation data available on compensation schemes. This prevents the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scrutiny of projects by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or civil society and removes a key element in the design of successful markets: some kind of discipline, including through the fear of sanction. Moreover, it means central government, when developing national policy cannot benefit from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This has been demonstrated in the admission by Defra that it knows offsetting has taken place, but does not know how much.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A simple, easy-to-search register of compensa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion schemes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would help overcome these weaknesses and ensure that successful approaches are replicated and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there are consequences for non-delivery. The data could allow the preparation of league tables comparing the performance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of local a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uthorities in protecting important biodiversity, replacing the scrapped National Performance Indicator regime. Again, this could increase competition between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> over the quality of provision, and allow civil society, citizens and media to highlight good (and weak) performers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition to this, international experience (such as Australia’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bushbroker</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> scheme, where offsets are listed on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bushbroker</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> website) has found that a registry of offsets helps buyers and sellers to find and deliver appropriate compensation measures easily.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Net Gain in Biodiversity</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We consider that a key requirement of a biodiversity offset system is the inclusion of a ‘net gain’ principle. Whilst there may be an argument against developers compensating for biodiversity loss incurred in the past and avoiding new costs to developers (and so only requiring ‘no net loss’ of biodiversity), we consider that a net gain principle is required since:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The past 100 years has seen a significant decline in the quality of national biodiversity. As a result, policymakers should ensure threatened species and habitats do not simply survive, but thrive and recover. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Natural Environment White Paper reflects this.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">International experience has shown that where planning systems give clearer guidance, for example that offsets should deliver a net gain in biodiversity, they deliver improved outcomes compared to vaguer formulations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The principle removes doubt for planners and developers.</span></li></ul><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We support the inclusion of ‘risk premiums’, or multipliers, in the current offsetting proposal, since habitat creation, re-creation and translocation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all have less chance of success than maintaining existing sites</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, it is important to note that this only compensates for the risk element; it does not ensure net gain in biodiversity even if the offsets fully meet their objectives. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We note that the only mechanism within the Green Paper to ensure net gain of biodiversity is in the strategic location of offsets. The strategic location of offsets to link fragmented habitats and provide corridors is important. However, it is unclear to what extent this will deliver net gain of biodiversity, particularly if offsets fail to deliver their targets. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A strengthened net gain principle for offsetting would not, however, be appropriate for every development, particularly small-scale activity. An </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appropriate threshold would be that for which Environmental Impact Assessments are required. This balances encouraging development and ensuring its impact on biodiversity is recognised.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Mandatory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Offset System</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Current government proposals favour a fully permissive approach to biodiversity offsetting. This is in part to comply with the government’s one-in one-out system to reduce red tape for businesses, including developers. There is also the argument that if offsetting is as good for developers as the government hopes (in terms of reducing planning delays and potentially costs), most developers will voluntarily use offsetting. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, international </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience shows that the most successful offset schemes are all based on regulation that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">mandates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> compensation for land-use changes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> There are several reasons for this, including:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without the certainty of a compulsory scheme, there is much less incentive for potential offset </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providers, like farmers and NGO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to make investments in developing conservation proposals.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This could result in a potential offset supply bottleneck, with insufficient providers available for developers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Giving developers the choice over whether they participate provides them with a negotiating advantage over LAs and is likely to lead to less conservation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A mandatory scheme would reduce transaction costs.</span></li></ul><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In our report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Nurturing Nature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, we strongly recommended the implementation of a pilot of a mandatory offsetting system. In the absence of this, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ran a cost-benefit analysis of a national compulsory offsetting scheme. This found that a compulsory scheme could add around £70.7 million to the total cost of development every year, around 0.1% of the annual value of new build construction in the UK (our extreme scenario saw a cost of up to £253.3 million a year). This sum would help meet the annual shortfall in biodiversity funding, estimated at £110.3–157.3 million.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Importantly, flexibility of delivery should be retained in a biodiversity offset system. For example, developers should be able to either develop compensation projects directly with offset providers, or via a habitat bank, etc. In addition, flexibility in payments should also be provided for, for example accommodating both lump-sum payments and instalments over an agreed period of time.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">15 October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>